285
00:16:50,941 --> 00:16:54,928
Rym: So it's Tech Day, and today we decided we were going to talk about tech support.

286
00:16:55,369 --> 00:17:01,380
Rym: Mostly in terms of doing tech support for friends or family or other associated malcontents.

287
00:17:01,640 --> 00:17:09,060
Scott: Yeah, we're not talking about the job of actually being a tech support guy because that's not a good job and we never had that job on purpose.

288
00:17:09,700 --> 00:17:10,321
Rym: I almost did.

289
00:17:10,382 --> 00:17:10,983
Rym: I kinda did.

290
00:17:11,023 --> 00:17:15,980
Rym: I mean, technically, I was supposed to look at the problem queue when I worked for ITS at RIT.

291
00:17:16,506 --> 00:17:16,739
Scott: Yeah.

292
00:17:17,020 --> 00:17:18,028
Rym: But I never did.

293
00:17:18,048 --> 00:17:19,439
Rym: I usually just did other fun work.

294
00:17:19,784 --> 00:17:20,048
Scott: Yep.

295
00:17:20,413 --> 00:17:20,839
Scott: Good idea.

296
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:23,680
Rym: Like sleep in my office or wander around campus.

297
00:17:24,420 --> 00:17:25,319
Scott: Much safer that way.

298
00:17:25,579 --> 00:17:25,721
Rym: Yeah.

299
00:17:26,002 --> 00:17:29,000
Rym: Maybe snoop through a professor's email because they had trouble with their email.

300
00:17:29,560 --> 00:17:29,720
Scott: Mhm.

301
00:17:30,482 --> 00:17:41,018
Scott: Well, but, you know, as intelligent computer guys we are, other people who aren't so computer intelligent often ask us, you know, "How do you do this?

302
00:17:41,058 --> 00:17:41,739
Scott: Help me with that,".

303
00:17:41,779 --> 00:17:42,180
Scott: blah blah blah.

304
00:17:42,881 --> 00:17:44,484
Rym: Now, it isn't just a problem for us.

305
00:17:44,544 --> 00:17:48,151
Rym: It's a problem that I think all computer geeks out there have run into.

306
00:17:49,013 --> 00:17:52,260
Rym: Your family decide they get a new computer and they bother you to help them with it.

307
00:17:52,680 --> 00:17:55,969
Rym: Your grandma calls you at four in the morning because their internet's broken.

308
00:17:56,892 --> 00:17:59,980
Rym: The lady who lives next door keeps asking you to fix your VCR.

309
00:18:00,460 --> 00:18:00,701
Scott: Mhm.

310
00:18:01,362 --> 00:18:05,311
Scott: I mean, it happens to a lot of people, you know, in some professions more than others.

311
00:18:05,371 --> 00:18:09,620
Scott: I mean, if you're a generic unskilled businessman, no one asks you any questions.

312
00:18:09,740 --> 00:18:17,300
Scott: But like, you know, if you're a tax lawyer, like my friend's dad, everyone always asks him around tax season, you know, questions and stuff.

313
00:18:17,440 --> 00:18:21,692
Scott: And my uncle's a dentist, so once in a while someone will come up to him and be like, "Can you look at my

314
00:18:21,732 --> 00:18:21,993
Scott: teeth?".

315
00:18:22,033 --> 00:18:23,658
Scott: And he always says, "Make an appointment at my

316
00:18:23,738 --> 00:18:24,059
Scott: office.".

317
00:18:25,260 --> 00:18:36,178
Scott: But when you're a computer guy, you don't, you know, unless you're someone who's like a PC doctor who people call up and you go to fix computers, then no one can really call you because it's not your job.

318
00:18:36,218 --> 00:18:37,260
Scott: You're working for someone else.

319
00:18:37,961 --> 00:18:42,251
Rym: But yet, people always seem to bother us about getting tech support.

320
00:18:42,672 --> 00:18:42,752
Rym: Mhm.

321
00:18:42,932 --> 00:18:46,360
Rym: I mean, it's getting to be a real problem in the geek industry.

322
00:18:46,741 --> 00:18:49,648
Scott: It's like, you know, there are actual people who do that for a living.

323
00:18:49,688 --> 00:18:51,232
Scott: You can call them and ask them questions.

324
00:18:51,292 --> 00:18:54,380
Scott: You can go on the internet and ask questions and someone will answer them for free.

325
00:18:55,060 --> 00:19:02,260
Rym: I think the real problem I have is that many of the people who ask for help really get very kind of angry if I don't help them.

326
00:19:02,921 --> 00:19:05,488
Scott: Yeah, they don't get angry at my uncle if he says, "Make an

327
00:19:05,528 --> 00:19:05,989
Scott: appointment.".

328
00:19:06,129 --> 00:19:10,540
Rym: Yeah, you don't get angry at the doctor friend who refuses to take your appendix out for you on his weekend.

329
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:13,650
Scott: Yeah, it's like, you want to get your appendix out, go to the hospital.

330
00:19:13,670 --> 00:19:16,140
Scott: There's a doctor there who's going to do it because he's getting paid.

331
00:19:16,840 --> 00:19:22,091
Rym: I mean, the idea came up and we decided to do the show because a while back, there's a lady who lives downstairs.

332
00:19:22,953 --> 00:19:25,519
Rym: There's a basement apartment on our house and an old lady lives in it.

333
00:19:26,521 --> 00:19:30,688
Rym: And she said her DVD player didn't work and she wanted me to go, like, fix it.

334
00:19:31,730 --> 00:19:37,180
Rym: And I wander into her house and I'm poking around and she just doesn't have the remote control for the TV.

335
00:19:37,700 --> 00:19:38,479
Scott: Oh, yeah, she found it.

336
00:19:38,840 --> 00:19:39,259
Rym: Oh, she did?

337
00:19:39,400 --> 00:19:39,487
Scott: Yeah.

338
00:19:39,880 --> 00:19:39,940
Scott: Oh.

339
00:19:40,561 --> 00:19:45,048
Rym: So I can't set up the input on the TV, so I can't make the DVD player work.

340
00:19:45,348 --> 00:19:53,360
Rym: And she's mad because I can't help her and I'm kind of ticked because I was going to go somewhere and instead I'm roped into helping someone do something that I really don't care about.

341
00:19:54,181 --> 00:19:58,058
Rym: And then I can't even do it because I don't have the equipment and they can't give it to me.

342
00:19:59,560 --> 00:20:06,154
Rym: People seem to just forget that computers are just like any other profession and it's my job.

343
00:20:06,534 --> 00:20:09,120
Rym: When I'm not doing my job, I often don't want to be doing my job.

344
00:20:10,241 --> 00:20:12,119
Scott: Yeah, the problem is I don't do my job at my job.

345
00:20:13,020 --> 00:20:13,149
Rym: Yeah.

346
00:20:13,701 --> 00:20:16,104
Scott: But my job isn't helping other people with computers.

347
00:20:16,184 --> 00:20:18,627
Scott: It's making computers do things they don't already do.

348
00:20:18,787 --> 00:20:19,508
Scott: That's what I do.

349
00:20:19,809 --> 00:20:20,750
Scott: You know, I can't.

350
00:20:20,790 --> 00:20:28,200
Scott: I have the knowledge and ability to help you with computer problems because I have to know those things in order to make computers do things they don't already do.

351
00:20:28,580 --> 00:20:32,889
Rym: Yeah, and I mean, a lot of times we love to just help someone with a computer, help someone with technology on their own.

352
00:20:33,350 --> 00:20:37,800
Rym: The only problem comes is that a lot of people seem to expect that no matter what, like at any time.

353
00:20:38,161 --> 00:20:40,839
Scott: Or a lot of people make it very difficult to help them.

354
00:20:41,800 --> 00:20:43,003
Rym: That's probably the worst one.

355
00:20:43,023 --> 00:20:48,376
Rym: I mean, if someone asks me, like, on aim, "Uh, my video card doesn't work, blah, blah, blah.

356
00:20:48,396 --> 00:20:48,696
Rym: What do I

357
00:20:48,737 --> 00:20:48,897
Rym: do?"

358
00:20:48,977 --> 00:20:49,659
Rym: I'll say, "Oh, do

359
00:20:49,699 --> 00:20:49,879
Rym: this.".

360
00:20:50,941 --> 00:20:56,000
Rym: If they don't do what I told them and then they bother me again, that's not cool.

361
00:20:56,620 --> 00:20:59,997
Scott: Yeah, if you don't like the answer I give you, uh, I got two words.

362
00:21:00,037 --> 00:21:00,218
Scott: "Tough

363
00:21:00,258 --> 00:21:00,459
Scott: shit.".

364
00:21:01,941 --> 00:21:06,852
Scott: You know, the worst is, see, I don't like to just tell people things or do things for people.

365
00:21:07,133 --> 00:21:10,020
Scott: I like to make sure that they know what I'm doing for them.

366
00:21:10,160 --> 00:21:12,179
Rym: Yeah, Scott, we're all aware of that.

367
00:21:12,760 --> 00:21:15,131
Scott: Yeah, I want to make sure you learn how to fish.

368
00:21:15,493 --> 00:21:16,920
Scott: You know, teach a man to fish and all that.

369
00:21:17,480 --> 00:21:20,930
Rym: Well, the problem is... Teach a man to build a fire and he's warm for a few days.

370
00:21:21,352 --> 00:21:23,440
Rym: Set a man on fire and he's warm for the rest of his life.

371
00:21:24,580 --> 00:21:25,358
Scott: That's a good one.

372
00:21:26,422 --> 00:21:33,659
Scott: No, but, uh, when I go up to you and you say, "Man, I really wish I had some fish," I go, "Here, I'll show you how to catch

373
00:21:33,699 --> 00:21:33,799
Scott: them.".

374
00:21:34,340 --> 00:21:40,800
Scott: And if I try to hand you the rod and you just refuse to take hold of it and demand that I catch fish for you, I'm just going to push you in the fucking lake.

375
00:21:41,281 --> 00:21:44,740
Scott: And then if you're indignant, fuck you, I'm going to piss on you while you're down there.

376
00:21:45,123 --> 00:21:45,214
Rym: Okay.

377
00:21:45,860 --> 00:21:52,840
Scott: I don't know, I just tried to think of something you would do to someone while you're standing on a dock and they're swimming in the lake crying for help and you want to kind of put them down even more.

378
00:21:53,040 --> 00:21:53,478
Rym: Just laugh.

379
00:21:54,060 --> 00:21:54,940
Scott: Yeah, laughing is good.

380
00:21:55,081 --> 00:21:58,099
Rym: And then when they try to climb back up into the dock, push them off and then laugh again.

381
00:21:59,021 --> 00:22:00,520
Rym: Repeat, add infant item.

382
00:22:01,860 --> 00:22:06,640
Scott: So, let's see, what kind of things make me pissed off at people when I try to give them tech support?

383
00:22:07,220 --> 00:22:13,260
Rym: Well, the main thing is that most people will... Well, not most people, because actually at least none of our friends seem to do this.

384
00:22:13,340 --> 00:22:17,439
Rym: It's mostly relatives and people who are, like, business acquaintances who do this to us.

385
00:22:18,240 --> 00:22:22,899
Rym: But, like, someone will say, "Hey, I'm having trouble with my computer, can you help

386
00:22:22,919 --> 00:22:23,020
Rym: me?".

387
00:22:23,120 --> 00:22:24,477
Rym: And I'll say, "Yeah, sure, what's

388
00:22:24,497 --> 00:22:24,720
Rym: wrong?".

389
00:22:24,820 --> 00:22:28,859
Rym: And they'll say something so vague, like, "Well, the internet doesn't

390
00:22:28,899 --> 00:22:29,080
Rym: work.".

391
00:22:30,081 --> 00:22:35,420
Scott: Yeah, if you cannot describe to me the problem specifically enough, I can't help you.

392
00:22:35,720 --> 00:22:37,120
Rym: Now, you don't have to be a technologist.

393
00:22:37,220 --> 00:22:43,440
Rym: You don't have to say, like, "Yeah, well, UDP is being blocked on this port and blah blah blah, but I know my blah blah blah

394
00:22:43,460 --> 00:22:43,540
Rym: blah.".

395
00:22:43,540 --> 00:22:48,200
Scott: Because if you know that already, you probably don't need my help and you're smart enough to find the answer on Google.

396
00:22:48,561 --> 00:22:53,520
Rym: Well, I mean, or either that or they actually have a difficult problem and my expertise might be able to help them.

397
00:22:53,920 --> 00:22:54,260
Rym: Yeah, they might.

398
00:22:54,400 --> 00:23:00,040
Rym: The problem is when people... It's like, for some reason, people treat computers completely differently the way they treat anything else.

399
00:23:00,661 --> 00:23:05,219
Rym: If some guy has a toaster and toast is stuck in it, he sticks a fork in there and just digs it out.

400
00:23:05,960 --> 00:23:13,900
Rym: But if his computer stops working, he doesn't actually look at the screen and read the error message or look and see if it's actually plugged in.

401
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:18,151
Rym: He just immediately throws his hands in the air, then he comes to us and says, "Hey, my computer doesn't work.

402
00:23:18,531 --> 00:23:20,135
Rym: It's obviously not my problem.

403
00:23:21,098 --> 00:23:21,699
Rym: I didn't cause

404
00:23:21,719 --> 00:23:21,900
Rym: this.".

405
00:23:22,781 --> 00:23:27,349
Scott: I think it's largely something caused by AOL and Microsoft and Dell.

406
00:23:27,429 --> 00:23:36,440
Scott: is that for so long, somehow, computers got this air of difficulty around them, which I can understand from the DOS days when they were kind of difficult to use.

407
00:23:37,160 --> 00:23:43,300
Rym: Computers are complex devices, and I think the problem is just that people try to treat them as though they're just in a dumb appliance.

408
00:23:44,120 --> 00:23:47,674
Rym: It should just do what I want it to do, but it's a multi-purpose device.

409
00:23:47,734 --> 00:23:49,360
Rym: It can do anything, like Zombocom.

410
00:23:49,860 --> 00:23:57,089
Scott: Yes, anything is possible, which is why it's not easy to use something that, you know... It's the old tool versus device thing, you know?

411
00:23:57,169 --> 00:23:59,980
Scott: I learned about this in some tech class at some point in RIT.

412
00:24:00,140 --> 00:24:02,279
Rym: Yeah, we talked about that in one of our tech classes, too.

413
00:24:02,962 --> 00:24:09,620
Scott: It's like a tool is something you have to know how to use, and there are different ways to use it, and it's a complex thing.

414
00:24:09,720 --> 00:24:13,620
Scott: A device is like you push a button and something happens, you know?

415
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:15,466
Scott: Like, you look at a saw.

416
00:24:15,827 --> 00:24:18,800
Scott: You don't just push the button on the saw and then the wood is cut.

417
00:24:18,860 --> 00:24:22,420
Scott: You have to know how to use the saw properly and all that stuff.

418
00:24:22,540 --> 00:24:23,644
Rym: Now, I could make a computer.

419
00:24:23,684 --> 00:24:24,427
Rym: that was a device.

420
00:24:24,487 --> 00:24:26,915
Rym: In fact, I did for IBM where I work.

421
00:24:27,056 --> 00:24:28,260
Rym: I made hundreds and hundreds of them.

422
00:24:28,802 --> 00:24:34,640
Rym: I could make a computer that is so simple and it can't break and it just has, like, there's a big desktop with five buttons.

423
00:24:34,720 --> 00:24:40,040
Rym: There's the email button, and there's the game button, and there's the web browser button, and it'll always work perfectly.

424
00:24:40,940 --> 00:24:43,739
Rym: Problem is, you can't do anything other than the buttons I already put in.

425
00:24:45,321 --> 00:24:48,712
Scott: By making something easier... Well, I'll explain this after.

426
00:24:48,732 --> 00:24:50,518
Scott: There's differences between easy to learn and easy to use.

427
00:24:52,105 --> 00:24:53,840
Rym: Yep, VI is a good example in that one.

428
00:24:53,940 --> 00:25:01,000
Scott: Yeah, but the easier to use and easier to learn you make something, the... Well, no.

429
00:25:01,220 --> 00:25:04,513
Scott: The easier to learn you make something, the less powerful it is.

430
00:25:04,533 --> 00:25:06,180
Scott: It's just a law of the universe.

431
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:10,640
Scott: I mean, the easiest thing to learn to use in the world is one button.

432
00:25:11,100 --> 00:25:11,442
Scott: Guess what?

433
00:25:11,523 --> 00:25:13,515
Scott: Something with one button can only do one thing.

434
00:25:15,341 --> 00:25:19,740
Scott: At most, it can do a few things if you learn Morse code, but then it's no longer easy to learn.

435
00:25:20,202 --> 00:25:23,073
Rym: It's like that easy button they sell from whatever office store.

436
00:25:23,274 --> 00:25:24,719
Rym: You hit the button and it says, "That was

437
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:24,900
Rym: easy.".

438
00:25:25,500 --> 00:25:26,908
Scott: Yeah, but no.

439
00:25:27,069 --> 00:25:29,040
Scott: Easy to learn and easy to use are two different things.

440
00:25:29,180 --> 00:25:36,580
Scott: Easy to learn means if you know nothing about it, you can figure out how it works and how to use it in a short amount of time, no matter how smart you are.

441
00:25:36,901 --> 00:25:38,008
Scott: Like a toaster.

442
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:39,658
Scott: It's not hard to learn a toaster.

443
00:25:39,678 --> 00:25:39,940
Scott: There's like...

444
00:25:40,542 --> 00:25:45,440
Rym: You'd be surprised how many people have been electrocuted by shoving metal objects into toasters while they were plugged in.

445
00:25:45,841 --> 00:25:46,402
Scott: Yeah, I know.

446
00:25:46,924 --> 00:25:52,940
Scott: But the point is, is you get the simple toaster, you put bread in the top and you push the thing down, it's relatively easy to learn.

447
00:25:53,420 --> 00:25:57,500
Scott: It only has one thing you really do, and it's kind of obvious the bread goes in the top.

448
00:25:58,301 --> 00:25:59,820
Scott: Ninety percent of people will get it right.

449
00:26:00,120 --> 00:26:02,028
Rym: I just picture like a guy laying there dead.

450
00:26:02,048 --> 00:26:04,740
Rym: There's half of a baby shoved into one side.

451
00:26:05,061 --> 00:26:08,860
Rym: There's like a loaf of bread squished in, still in its package on the other side.

452
00:26:09,202 --> 00:26:11,280
Rym: It's plugged into a 220 line and it's on fire.

453
00:26:11,501 --> 00:26:12,220
Scott: And he's in the shower.

454
00:26:15,121 --> 00:26:17,448
Scott: But easy to use is something completely different.

455
00:26:17,528 --> 00:26:22,000
Scott: Something can be hard as hell to learn, but at the same time, easy as hell to use.

456
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:23,274
Scott: Yep, like a V.I

457
00:26:24,100 --> 00:26:24,662
Scott: V.I.,

458
00:26:24,743 --> 00:26:26,509
Scott: if you don't know, is... Well, there's also

459
00:26:26,590 --> 00:26:27,152
Scott: V.I.M.,

460
00:26:27,232 --> 00:26:28,999
Scott: which is what people who are sane use.

461
00:26:29,644 --> 00:26:29,731
Rym: Yeah.

462
00:26:30,441 --> 00:26:31,765
Scott: But it's basically the same thing.

463
00:26:31,825 --> 00:26:33,390
Scott: It's a text editor for the computer.

464
00:26:33,491 --> 00:26:36,300
Scott: It essentially does the same thing Notepad does.

465
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:41,260
Rym: It's just, it's very... For people who aren't familiar with Linux, it's very obtuse.

466
00:26:42,021 --> 00:26:47,635
Scott: Yeah, the way it works is it works on keyboard commands, and it starts off in command mode.

467
00:26:47,675 --> 00:26:49,379
Scott: It has two modes, command mode and...

468
00:26:49,640 --> 00:26:54,180
Rym: Well, you know, we can just simplify this because anyone who knows what we're talking about knows, and if they don't, they don't care.

469
00:26:54,440 --> 00:26:55,637
Scott: Yeah, maybe we could do a show on V.I.

470
00:26:55,980 --> 00:26:56,980
Rym: We could, actually.

471
00:26:57,060 --> 00:26:57,580
Rym: Yeah, that's a good show.

472
00:26:57,780 --> 00:26:59,583
Rym: But here, for those of you who don't know what V.I.

473
00:26:59,683 --> 00:27:00,685
Rym: is, I'll say this.

474
00:27:00,906 --> 00:27:09,120
Rym: If you want to save the thing you're typing and exit the program, you hit escape, shift, colon, w, q, enter.

475
00:27:09,642 --> 00:27:09,882
Scott: Yep.

476
00:27:10,524 --> 00:27:13,453
Scott: There's no way for you to learn that just by playing with it.

477
00:27:13,513 --> 00:27:14,617
Scott: It's non-obvious.

478
00:27:14,737 --> 00:27:15,740
Scott: Very non-obvious.

479
00:27:16,100 --> 00:27:18,580
Rym: However, it's very easy to use once you know it.

480
00:27:18,940 --> 00:27:22,065
Scott: Once you know it, you can do crazy stuff in V.I.

481
00:27:22,245 --> 00:27:31,360
Scott: I can, like, delete every other line in the file that contains the word "the" and paste them all at the end of the file by pushing, like, three buttons.

482
00:27:31,781 --> 00:27:37,160
Scott: If you want to do that in Notepad, you have to sit there for hours and hours cutting, pasting, cutting, pasting, cutting, pasting.

483
00:27:37,480 --> 00:27:41,550
Scott: It's hard to do things in Notepad, but it's very easy to figure out how to do them.

484
00:27:41,991 --> 00:27:42,091
Scott: In

485
00:27:42,152 --> 00:27:42,593
Scott: V.I.,

486
00:27:42,633 --> 00:27:45,560
Scott: it's very easy to do things, but it's hard to figure out how to do them.

487
00:27:46,640 --> 00:27:54,260
Rym: Now, I guess to not stray too off topic, the advice I guess we have for people who are going to ask techs like us for computer help.

488
00:27:54,660 --> 00:27:55,703
Rym: Now, this doesn't apply to people.

489
00:27:55,744 --> 00:27:57,128
Rym: we help because we want to help.

490
00:27:57,168 --> 00:28:00,680
Rym: I mean, we have a lot of fun actually teaching people to do certain kinds of things.

491
00:28:00,781 --> 00:28:02,059
Scott: Especially when they want to learn.

492
00:28:02,720 --> 00:28:05,470
Rym: Yeah, like if someone comes up to me like, "I want to learn how to use

493
00:28:05,490 --> 00:28:05,831
Rym: Linux."

494
00:28:06,011 --> 00:28:08,440
Rym: Like, that's awesome, and I'll sit there for an hour and show them how to use Linux.

495
00:28:09,780 --> 00:28:18,100
Rym: But we're directing this mostly at people who ask techies for help with their problems and don't do due diligence.

496
00:28:18,620 --> 00:28:20,225
Rym: This is how to do your due diligence.

497
00:28:20,506 --> 00:28:24,500
Rym: so other techies, because all techies seem to want the same thing, don't cry or hit you.

498
00:28:25,200 --> 00:28:27,020
Scott: Number one, vocabulary.

499
00:28:27,921 --> 00:28:37,380
Rym: If you don't know what your problem is and you can't describe the problem, you really can't blame the techie when they have no idea what you're talking about.

500
00:28:37,600 --> 00:28:44,720
Scott: My grandma is the worst one with this, because they say, "Close the window," and she doesn't know what a window is and she doesn't know how to close it or what closing means.

501
00:28:44,840 --> 00:28:46,215
Rym: Or they'll call you and say, "The kajigger's

502
00:28:46,255 --> 00:28:46,559
Rym: broken.".

503
00:28:46,700 --> 00:28:51,915
Scott: Yeah, so that leaves me with the word "the," which basically means if I can't communicate with you, I can't help you.

504
00:28:52,637 --> 00:28:53,840
Scott: You're beyond help, go away.

505
00:28:54,181 --> 00:28:56,125
Rym: Now, this isn't saying that you have to know the jargon.

506
00:28:56,526 --> 00:29:02,960
Rym: It's just that you have to have some sort of cognitive understanding of something about your problem.

507
00:29:03,140 --> 00:29:08,592
Scott: You don't need to know what UDP means for me to help you, but you do need to know what window means and what close means.

508
00:29:08,672 --> 00:29:13,966
Scott: and yet, you know, what a menu is and all those sorts of... There's a level that you have to reach.

509
00:29:13,986 --> 00:29:15,412
Scott: that's like the minimum requirement.

510
00:29:15,693 --> 00:29:17,400
Scott: You can know more than that and it's helpful.

511
00:29:17,480 --> 00:29:23,220
Scott: You don't have to know what SATA is for me to help you, though, but you do have to know what the mouse is.

512
00:29:23,581 --> 00:29:23,802
Rym: Yep.

513
00:29:24,505 --> 00:29:27,419
Rym: Now, two, know what your problem actually is.

514
00:29:28,440 --> 00:29:33,596
Rym: Now, I'm not saying know, like, 'cause if you know what the problem is, you can fix it, but know how to describe your problem.

515
00:29:33,636 --> 00:29:35,080
Rym: It ties in very much with vocabulary.

516
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:41,337
Rym: If your screen is black and you just sit there and stare at it and then call me and say, "My computer's broken.

517
00:29:41,357 --> 00:29:41,758
Rym: I can't help

518
00:29:41,798 --> 00:29:41,899
Rym: you.".

519
00:29:42,581 --> 00:29:46,448
Rym: If you call me and say, "All right, I was using my computer and suddenly it turned off.

520
00:29:46,649 --> 00:29:47,551
Rym: The light's not on.

521
00:29:47,591 --> 00:29:49,334
Rym: When I hit the button, it doesn't turn back on.

522
00:29:49,595 --> 00:29:50,797
Rym: The cable is plugged in.

523
00:29:51,138 --> 00:29:51,499
Rym: What do I

524
00:29:51,539 --> 00:29:51,639
Rym: do?".

525
00:29:52,201 --> 00:29:53,264
Rym: That's a good question.

526
00:29:53,284 --> 00:29:53,986
Rym: Mm-hmm.

527
00:29:54,729 --> 00:29:56,535
Scott: It shows that you tried to do something.

528
00:29:56,575 --> 00:30:02,140
Scott: I mean, everyone... There are people with problem-solving skills and people without problem-solving skills.

529
00:30:02,240 --> 00:30:12,940
Scott: The thing is, even if you have problem-solving skills, if you don't have knowledge about the thing you're trying to, you know, solve the problem of, you're not gonna come up with a solution.

530
00:30:13,080 --> 00:30:20,380
Scott: Like, if there's a problem with my car, I can kind of figure it out, but I don't have enough knowledge about the inner workings of the car to be right all the time.

531
00:30:20,882 --> 00:30:21,765
Scott: Or to fix it.

532
00:30:22,046 --> 00:30:25,700
Rym: However, I mean, problem-solving skills has nothing to do with your technological prowess.

533
00:30:26,220 --> 00:30:39,000
Rym: If you have problem-solving skills, even if you don't have the knowledge to solve the problem at hand, you have the ability to at least narrow down the problem and then be able to explain to someone what you think the problem is.

534
00:30:39,660 --> 00:30:40,669
Scott: And describe the problem.

535
00:30:40,709 --> 00:30:41,859
Scott: Describing the problem is key.

536
00:30:42,180 --> 00:30:42,742
Rym: Like my car.

537
00:30:42,822 --> 00:30:47,600
Rym: My car broke down while I was driving to a convention in Indiana, in the middle of nowhere in Indiana.

538
00:30:47,620 --> 00:30:52,575
Rym: I end up going up into Michigan to do a mechanic, and I knew jack all about cars back then.

539
00:30:52,916 --> 00:30:53,979
Rym: I know slightly more now.

540
00:30:55,040 --> 00:30:58,578
Rym: And I pulled in, and the mechanic's like, "What's wrong with your

541
00:30:58,619 --> 00:30:58,820
Rym: car?".

542
00:30:59,241 --> 00:31:06,819
Rym: And I had no idea what was wrong with it, but I was able to tell him, "Well, whenever I'm idling under 2,000 RPM, it makes a rattling

543
00:31:06,879 --> 00:31:07,199
Rym: noise.".

544
00:31:08,062 --> 00:31:13,314
Rym: And the check engine light came on about 40 miles ago, and there's some knocking.

545
00:31:13,856 --> 00:31:14,357
Rym: A little bit.

546
00:31:14,537 --> 00:31:15,560
Rym: At least I think it's knocking.

547
00:31:17,203 --> 00:31:20,380
Rym: And I explained everything I could, and I gave him as much information as I could.

548
00:31:20,960 --> 00:31:22,091
Rym: And then he was like, "Oh, it sounds like

549
00:31:22,112 --> 00:31:22,273
Rym: this.".

550
00:31:22,293 --> 00:31:22,900
Rym: And then he went to work.

551
00:31:23,280 --> 00:31:27,780
Rym: And it probably saved me several hundred dollars worth of labor of him sitting there trying to figure out what my problem was.

552
00:31:28,220 --> 00:31:33,140
Scott: Yeah, this is why cars have that cool diagnostic thing where they plug the little computer in and it tells them what's wrong with the car.

553
00:31:33,860 --> 00:31:35,188
Scott: But that's not perfect.

554
00:31:35,550 --> 00:31:37,320
Scott: And computers don't have such a thing.

555
00:31:37,740 --> 00:31:40,639
Rym: Though you know what computers do have, and this ties in very well.

556
00:31:41,280 --> 00:31:41,938
Rym: Error messages.

557
00:31:42,880 --> 00:31:43,497
Scott: Read them!

558
00:31:44,362 --> 00:31:51,480
Rym: If nothing else, if you have a problem with your computer and you're going to ask someone like us for help, write down whatever the computer told you when the thing broke.

559
00:31:51,820 --> 00:31:55,100
Rym: Because whatever it told you was probably very relevant to the problem at hand.

560
00:31:55,440 --> 00:31:58,420
Scott: That's the worst thing, is people who don't read the screen.

561
00:31:58,640 --> 00:32:02,560
Scott: It's like, people will come to me with what the error message said sometimes.

562
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:08,359
Scott: And they'll be like, "The error message said 'DVD drive can't read the DVD

563
00:32:08,399 --> 00:32:08,600
Scott: drive.'".

564
00:32:08,681 --> 00:32:10,356
Scott: And I'll be like, "Oh, what do you think that

565
00:32:10,436 --> 00:32:10,759
Scott: means?".

566
00:32:11,182 --> 00:32:13,093
Scott: And they'll be like, "Uh, what did it

567
00:32:13,194 --> 00:32:13,556
Scott: say?".

568
00:32:14,442 --> 00:32:15,375
Scott: "You can't read the DVD

569
00:32:15,415 --> 00:32:15,598
Scott: drive.".

570
00:32:15,800 --> 00:32:16,690
Scott: "So what's wrong with your

571
00:32:16,710 --> 00:32:17,095
Scott: computer?".

572
00:32:18,711 --> 00:32:19,337
Scott: "The DVD's

573
00:32:19,377 --> 00:32:19,660
Scott: broken?".

574
00:32:19,781 --> 00:32:20,370
Scott: "Yes!".

575
00:32:21,321 --> 00:32:22,385
Scott: "Yes, that's what it said.

576
00:32:22,486 --> 00:32:25,617
Scott: Why did you have to call me to ask me what something

577
00:32:25,738 --> 00:32:25,818
Scott: is?".

578
00:32:26,542 --> 00:32:27,308
Scott: "Are you illiterate?

579
00:32:27,328 --> 00:32:28,517
Scott: You needed me to read it for

580
00:32:28,558 --> 00:32:28,679
Scott: you?".

581
00:32:29,561 --> 00:32:29,947
Rym: Read!

582
00:32:29,968 --> 00:32:30,639
Scott: Read, read, read!

583
00:32:30,960 --> 00:32:43,160
Rym: I blame mostly the fact that many computer programs and many things on the internet, and just many things, especially made for people who don't know much about computers, are set up where they'll give you a lot of text that you can ignore and still use the program.

584
00:32:43,740 --> 00:32:47,320
Rym: So people are so used to just clicking OK on anything no matter what and never actually reading.

585
00:32:48,280 --> 00:32:52,200
Rym: The worst are, like, some applications, Lotus Notes is notorious for this.

586
00:32:52,600 --> 00:33:04,620
Rym: When I upgraded Lotus Notes at work, I had to upgrade from version 6 to version 7, it warned me before I started the installer that at several points an error message would pop up, and I should just click OK and let it continue.

587
00:33:05,840 --> 00:33:10,500
Rym: Now, I read that and I understood, all right, those errors must be spurious, something's broken, whatever.

588
00:33:11,060 --> 00:33:15,700
Rym: But that happens often enough where people get used to ignoring errors because they don't think they're useful.

589
00:33:16,380 --> 00:33:16,561
Scott: Mm-hmm.

590
00:33:17,263 --> 00:33:21,418
Scott: At the same point, why the hell didn't you just make it so those errors didn't show up?

591
00:33:21,458 --> 00:33:21,980
Scott: What's wrong with you?

592
00:33:21,980 --> 00:33:22,742
Scott: No, don't ask me.

593
00:33:22,823 --> 00:33:28,100
Rym: Lotus Notes is... I can't describe to you the depths of my hatred for Lotus Notes.

594
00:33:28,480 --> 00:33:30,613
Scott: Yeah, it's not, what we're saying here is not 100% the fault of the user.

595
00:33:31,960 --> 00:33:37,540
Scott: Sometimes people who write shitty software deserve just as much of a beating for encouraging the shitty user.

596
00:33:38,062 --> 00:33:40,260
Rym: Yes, I mean, case in point, PC load letter?

597
00:33:40,900 --> 00:33:41,221
Scott: Yeah.

598
00:33:41,241 --> 00:33:49,820
Scott: If you make a car that explodes and then someone drives it poorly and it explodes, it's not just the poor driver at fault.

599
00:33:50,320 --> 00:33:56,140
Rym: But even in that case, write down whatever cryptic bullshit the computer told you and give it to a techie.

600
00:33:56,480 --> 00:33:59,420
Rym: They'll at least look on Google and try to figure it out.

601
00:33:59,681 --> 00:34:02,760
Scott: Yeah, you can look on Google before you come and ask us.

602
00:34:02,940 --> 00:34:04,760
Rym: Yes, that is number three, Google.

603
00:34:05,461 --> 00:34:11,340
Scott: If you have looked on Google for your answer before coming to me, I am a thousand times more likely to help you.

604
00:34:11,780 --> 00:34:15,320
Rym: Yes, especially since the first thing I do when someone comes to me is look on Google.

605
00:34:15,880 --> 00:34:16,643
Scott: Yeah, what do you think?

606
00:34:16,683 --> 00:34:18,590
Scott: We freaking know everything about computers?

607
00:34:18,851 --> 00:34:21,360
Scott: Well, no, we only know 99% of a thing about computers.

608
00:34:22,002 --> 00:34:26,020
Scott: And that means that your problem, we don't know the answer, Google's where we go.

609
00:34:26,141 --> 00:34:28,859
Rym: There are some people at my job, my work, because I'm good at what I do.

610
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:41,560
Rym: And the problem is, I don't know a lot about certain subjects, but people come to me about every technological subject on the earth all the time because I have this reputation in my office for being like the guy who knows everything.

611
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:47,280
Rym: And all I do, quite literally, so if any of my coworkers are listening, I've just revealed my secret.

612
00:34:47,980 --> 00:34:54,520
Rym: When someone asks me something, I kind of shrug it off and then I Google it and then I come right back a minute later with the answer.

613
00:34:55,221 --> 00:34:55,522
Scott: Yeah.

614
00:34:55,542 --> 00:34:56,164
Rym: That's all I do.

615
00:34:56,425 --> 00:34:56,846
Scott: That's it.

616
00:34:57,508 --> 00:35:00,437
Rym: I mean, I had a Cisco switch and it did something weird.

617
00:35:00,477 --> 00:35:01,300
Rym: It gave an error message.

618
00:35:01,720 --> 00:35:06,238
Rym: I typed the error message into Google and I found the answer and then I went back and said, "Oh, and then everyone thought I was a Cisco

619
00:35:06,298 --> 00:35:06,619
Rym: expert.".

620
00:35:06,860 --> 00:35:12,080
Scott: It's like there's this library in a town and the library has all the answers to everyone's questions in the whole universe.

621
00:35:12,380 --> 00:35:14,566
Scott: But there's only one literate guy in the whole town.

622
00:35:15,088 --> 00:35:19,580
Scott: And everyone just comes to the literate guy and he goes into the library and finds the answer.

623
00:35:19,680 --> 00:35:20,162
Scott: You know what?

624
00:35:20,663 --> 00:35:26,580
Scott: If you learn to fucking read, you can go in the library yourself and save that literate guy a lot of trouble so he can get on with his life.

625
00:35:26,820 --> 00:35:37,120
Rym: Now, by the same token, if a problem is obtuse or complex enough, you'll Google and you'll find the answer, but the answer won't help you because it's something archaic or difficult to understand or full of jargon.

626
00:35:37,120 --> 00:35:38,765
Scott: Or you actually have to modify.

627
00:35:38,785 --> 00:35:43,619
Scott: I mean, there's most problems, some guy will be like, "This is my problem and then this is how I solved

628
00:35:43,640 --> 00:35:43,680
Scott: it.".

629
00:35:43,800 --> 00:35:49,032
Scott: And if you were smart, you would realize that doing exactly that won't work exactly in your situation.

630
00:35:49,052 --> 00:35:52,580
Scott: You have to modify that procedure for solving your problem in some way.

631
00:35:52,720 --> 00:36:01,300
Rym: But even in that case, if you come to someone like us and you say, "Yeah, I looked on Google and it said to do this, but I wasn't sure so I wanted to ask you," that's fine.

632
00:36:01,480 --> 00:36:09,759
Scott: Yeah, like if you come to me with a procedure and your problem and then all you need to do is modify that procedure to your specific situation, that's terrific.

633
00:36:09,799 --> 00:36:10,220
Scott: I'll do that.

634
00:36:10,622 --> 00:36:13,140
Rym: Now, if you searched MSN, you can go to hell.

635
00:36:16,930 --> 00:36:17,340
Rym: Just Google.

636
00:36:18,020 --> 00:36:23,720
Scott: If you're searching MSN anyway, then you're the kind of person who is not probably going to be getting help.

637
00:36:24,360 --> 00:36:28,047
Rym: Now, I would have said our fourth thing is read the manual.

638
00:36:28,347 --> 00:36:35,180
Rym: However, I will say that the vast majority of documentation for technological things out there these days is pathetic.

639
00:36:36,122 --> 00:36:38,660
Rym: So, I don't fault you for not reading the manual.

640
00:36:38,780 --> 00:36:40,706
Scott: I don't fault you for not reading the manual.

641
00:36:41,108 --> 00:36:45,080
Scott: I do fault you for not attempting to find or read the manual.

642
00:36:45,540 --> 00:36:53,120
Rym: Yeah, my parents gave this to me and they paid like $3,000 or $4,000 for it in the '80s, but it's a VHS camcorder.

643
00:36:53,600 --> 00:36:55,828
Rym: It takes freaking giant lead acid batteries.

644
00:36:56,289 --> 00:36:58,356
Rym: It hurts my shoulder to use.

645
00:36:58,376 --> 00:36:59,540
Rym: It's a giant camcorder.

646
00:37:00,160 --> 00:37:07,940
Rym: And it came with a 60-page book that goes into great detail every single bit of this camcorder.

647
00:37:08,301 --> 00:37:11,072
Rym: And then in the back, there's like 10 pages worth of troubleshooting.

648
00:37:11,374 --> 00:37:12,940
Rym: And it's a full-on expert system.

649
00:37:13,420 --> 00:37:20,360
Rym: If this is the problem, or if you're having this problem, then answer this list of questions and at the end we'll tell you exactly what's wrong.

650
00:37:21,160 --> 00:37:23,012
Rym: And people don't write manuals like that anymore.

651
00:37:23,354 --> 00:37:24,240
Rym: It's really kind of sad.

652
00:37:24,920 --> 00:37:26,603
Scott: No, they write manuals to be shitty.

653
00:37:26,643 --> 00:37:35,280
Scott: That way, see, it boggles my mind that companies do everything in their power to reduce the number of people that call tech support.

654
00:37:35,681 --> 00:37:42,600
Scott: Because the more people that call tech support, especially under warranty, which is when most people call tech support, costs them money.

655
00:37:43,060 --> 00:37:49,480
Scott: It's basically this money sinkhole that they have to have in order to not piss off all their customers and go out of business.

656
00:37:50,580 --> 00:37:57,180
Scott: But at the same time, they make things so shitty in the first place that everyone has to call tech support.

657
00:37:57,460 --> 00:37:57,921
Scott: You know what?

658
00:37:58,021 --> 00:38:08,740
Scott: If you made your stuff less shitty and had better manuals and all that, you would save more money on tech support than by getting Indians to do it and then having long on-hold lines.

659
00:38:08,820 --> 00:38:11,045
Rym: No, I have a lot of theories about that, actually.

660
00:38:11,446 --> 00:38:13,772
Rym: Because I put tactical writing in all that on my resume.

661
00:38:13,832 --> 00:38:17,220
Rym: I actually have written quite a body of documentation in my day.

662
00:38:18,201 --> 00:38:25,540
Rym: And it seems to me that actual good technical writers are few and far between and demand fairly high salaries.

663
00:38:26,081 --> 00:38:32,460
Rym: So most people don't seem to see the value in hiring these people to just write a manual for a program.

664
00:38:32,540 --> 00:38:34,207
Rym: Oh, we'll make the intern write the manual.

665
00:38:34,468 --> 00:38:37,260
Rym: Why would we hire someone at $80,000 a year just to write a frickin' book?

666
00:38:37,781 --> 00:38:38,262
Scott: Oh, let's see.

667
00:38:38,302 --> 00:38:45,940
Scott: If we hire one guy for $80,000 a year, he can write all the manuals for all our products and then decrease our tech support costs by millions.

668
00:38:47,903 --> 00:38:52,953
Scott: Oh, the businessmen are stupid and businessmen shouldn't make technology decisions ever.

669
00:38:53,193 --> 00:38:56,720
Scott: But they should make business decisions because technology people can't make business decisions for shit.

670
00:38:57,340 --> 00:39:03,016
Rym: Now, my other theory about this... Well, I shouldn't say the word "theory" because people get pissed, but I'm gonna say the word "theory" anyway.

671
00:39:03,036 --> 00:39:03,638
Rym: Haha!

672
00:39:03,698 --> 00:39:04,340
Rym: Colloquialisms.

673
00:39:05,400 --> 00:39:06,740
Scott: What about your hypothesis?

674
00:39:07,823 --> 00:39:09,214
Rym: Yeah, my conjecture.

675
00:39:09,335 --> 00:39:09,920
Rym: My supposition.

676
00:39:10,643 --> 00:39:10,960
Scott: Conclusion!

677
00:39:11,602 --> 00:39:11,683
Scott: Ah!

678
00:39:12,092 --> 00:39:12,194
Scott: Ah!

679
00:39:12,378 --> 00:39:12,439
Scott: Ah!

680
00:39:15,301 --> 00:39:15,441
Rym: Alright.

681
00:39:15,722 --> 00:39:21,980
Rym: I've noticed, and I noticed it today because I got... I can't use any names, but I'm involved in a project right now.

682
00:39:22,680 --> 00:39:34,500
Rym: And the guy who's in charge of the routers for the project, you know, like the Cisco routers, sends me an email and the first word in it is "irregardless," which is not a fucking word.

683
00:39:35,020 --> 00:39:36,137
Scott: No, it is not.

684
00:39:36,380 --> 00:39:36,521
Rym: Well, no.

685
00:39:36,541 --> 00:39:38,129
Rym: I guess technically it is a derived word.

686
00:39:38,350 --> 00:39:40,259
Rym: However, it does not mean what you think it means.

687
00:39:40,743 --> 00:39:42,177
Scott: I don't think that means what you think it means.

688
00:39:42,820 --> 00:39:44,063
Rym: Two, it was not capitalized.

689
00:39:44,103 --> 00:39:45,466
Rym: And three, there was no comma after it.

690
00:39:45,827 --> 00:39:51,280
Rym: And then, he just pissed broken grammar into my screen.

691
00:39:52,120 --> 00:39:55,091
Rym: And then, at the end, he said something.

692
00:39:55,111 --> 00:39:57,540
Rym: And then there was a forwarded message from a tech from Cisco.

693
00:39:58,140 --> 00:40:01,229
Rym: This is like Cisco's external account support.

694
00:40:01,570 --> 00:40:03,555
Rym: This is the face of Cisco talking to me.

695
00:40:03,575 --> 00:40:05,320
Rym: And it was even worse.

696
00:40:06,600 --> 00:40:07,080
Scott: Inconceivable.

697
00:40:09,721 --> 00:40:22,220
Rym: And I've noticed this in almost all my professional dealings out there in the corporate world is that the vast majority of people, even people in high-level positions, vice presidents, presidents, CEOs, they can't communicate.

698
00:40:22,640 --> 00:40:23,743
Rym: They can't write for shit.

699
00:40:23,903 --> 00:40:24,745
Rym: They don't know how to spell.

700
00:40:24,925 --> 00:40:25,667
Rym: They don't know grammar.

701
00:40:25,827 --> 00:40:28,213
Rym: They can't communicate their ideas effectively.

702
00:40:28,754 --> 00:40:30,899
Rym: If they have a speech to give, someone writes it for them.

703
00:40:33,161 --> 00:40:33,542
Rym: I don't know.

704
00:40:33,562 --> 00:40:34,765
Rym: It bothers me.

705
00:40:34,865 --> 00:40:41,400
Rym: I really can't express to my boss and some of the people just how stupid some of the other people I deal with are.

706
00:40:42,220 --> 00:40:42,340
Scott: Yeah.

707
00:40:42,501 --> 00:40:45,867
Scott: I think we've gone on long enough about how people can't communicate their problems to us.

708
00:40:46,288 --> 00:40:52,180
Scott: But what's even worse, and sometimes, is when I tell you the solution and then you fail to do what I told you.

709
00:40:52,500 --> 00:40:52,963
Rym: Oh, God.

710
00:40:53,144 --> 00:40:56,200
Rym: I have a lot of non-technical stories about that in my old club.

711
00:40:56,681 --> 00:40:57,141
Rym: Yeah.

712
00:40:57,842 --> 00:41:10,140
Scott: But I mean, when I tell you to do X, Y, and Z, and then you don't like the answer, or you don't listen to me in some way, or you misinterpret what I told you.

713
00:41:10,140 --> 00:41:11,463
Rym: No, it's not like you screwed up.

714
00:41:11,503 --> 00:41:17,074
Rym: Like, if we tell you to recompile your kernel and you do it wrong, or, I mean, that's fine, whatever.

715
00:41:17,094 --> 00:41:20,100
Rym: We should have said more detail or it was a difficult thing.

716
00:41:20,820 --> 00:41:23,150
Rym: But if we tell you to recompile the kernel and you say, "What?

717
00:41:23,310 --> 00:41:23,772
Rym: Fuck that.

718
00:41:23,853 --> 00:41:24,877
Scott: I shouldn't have to recompile my

719
00:41:24,917 --> 00:41:25,198
Scott: kernel."

720
00:41:26,302 --> 00:41:28,460
Scott: Well, that's what you're going to have to do, like it or not.

721
00:41:28,860 --> 00:41:31,067
Rym: People just don't like getting bad answers.

722
00:41:31,990 --> 00:41:34,920
Rym: Oh, man, there's so many work anecdotes that I really can't relate.

723
00:41:35,120 --> 00:41:35,240
Rym: Yeah.

724
00:41:35,461 --> 00:41:39,549
Scott: It's so weird, though, because if you go to a mechanic and he says, "You need a new transmission," right?

725
00:41:39,990 --> 00:41:44,520
Scott: Sometimes they might be nutty and try to go to a different mechanic and get told the same thing.

726
00:41:44,840 --> 00:41:54,738
Rym: It's like the crazy people who, like, their kid has a flu or something, or a cold, and they go to the doctor like, "He has pneumonia, blah, blah, blah," and the doctor says, "He has a cold.

727
00:41:55,239 --> 00:41:55,399
Rym: Go

728
00:41:55,459 --> 00:41:55,760
Rym: home.".

729
00:41:56,161 --> 00:41:57,025
Rym: And then, "I want a second

730
00:41:57,065 --> 00:41:57,346
Rym: opinion.".

731
00:41:57,366 --> 00:41:59,937
Rym: They go to another doctor, and that other doctor says, "He has a

732
00:41:59,997 --> 00:42:00,359
Rym: cold.".

733
00:42:01,560 --> 00:42:01,861
Scott: Yep.

734
00:42:03,104 --> 00:42:09,880
Scott: But then, you know, eventually those people seem to suck it up and, you know, pay the mechanic to get a new transmission, because they have to.

735
00:42:10,460 --> 00:42:22,200
Scott: But when people have a computer problem, and I tell them, "You're going to have to, you know, back up all your files and then format your drive," and whatever, you know, no matter how many times they'll do it, they won't do it.

736
00:42:22,360 --> 00:42:24,800
Scott: They'll just suffer with their shit spyware or whatever they've got.

737
00:42:26,060 --> 00:42:27,604
Scott: You know, I'm like, "Fine, you want it that way?

738
00:42:27,804 --> 00:42:28,385
Scott: If I have it that

739
00:42:28,425 --> 00:42:28,545
Scott: way.".

740
00:42:28,586 --> 00:42:33,395
Scott: But then, they come back and they'll complain their computer's slow and shitty, and I'll be like, "What did I tell you before?

741
00:42:33,556 --> 00:42:35,099
Scott: Go away, or I'll kill

742
00:42:35,119 --> 00:42:35,199
Scott: you.".

743
00:42:36,081 --> 00:42:45,240
Rym: I mean, I guess the moral of the story is just that, don't, I mean, we're technologists, and we enjoy helping people, but computers aren't special.

744
00:42:45,700 --> 00:42:52,920
Rym: I mean, your car needs oil changes and regular maintenance, and you either know how to do it yourself, or you take it to someone and pay him money to do it for you.

745
00:42:53,502 --> 00:42:54,505
Rym: Your computer's no different.

746
00:42:54,866 --> 00:42:58,940
Rym: You either have to know how to do the maintenance on it, or pay someone to do it for you.

747
00:42:59,720 --> 00:43:15,815
Scott: Yep, those are pretty much your choices, and you should be glad that, you know, mechanics don't work on cars for free, but computer people out there, some of them will help you for free, because it's actually less labor-intensive to work on a computer than to work on a car, and you don't usually need money for parts all the time.

748
00:43:15,855 --> 00:43:18,300
Scott: It's mostly software, which is mostly free.

749
00:43:18,921 --> 00:43:30,620
Scott: So, you know, you should be very, very thankful that someone will even talk to you for no money whatsoever when it comes to a problem with your computer, instead of just saying, "Give me money or leave," which is what the mechanic will tell you for your car.

750
00:43:31,020 --> 00:43:36,160
Rym: Yep, so actually, actually, there was a mechanic friend of my dad's who did a brake job on my car for free.

751
00:43:36,588 --> 00:43:36,780
Scott: Awesome.

752
00:43:36,940 --> 00:43:37,959
Rym: He was an awesome dude.

753
00:43:38,380 --> 00:43:38,722
Scott: Yeah.

754
00:43:39,005 --> 00:43:41,080
Scott: Did he actually give you brake pads and everything for free?

755
00:43:41,541 --> 00:43:46,360
Rym: Uh, I think I bought all the parts, but he did all the labor, and he had some of the parts laying around.

756
00:43:46,460 --> 00:43:48,605
Scott: Alright, yeah.

757
00:43:48,625 --> 00:43:54,598
Scott: But I mean, you should be so thankful that you should be, like, kissing feet, and if you fail to communicate...

758
00:43:55,661 --> 00:43:56,023
Rym: Okay.

759
00:43:56,949 --> 00:43:58,520
Rym: You just want people to kiss your feet, that's all.

760
00:43:58,640 --> 00:43:59,384
Scott: No, not really.

761
00:43:59,585 --> 00:44:02,200
Scott: Actually, I don't want you to kiss my feet, but that's kind of you.

762
00:44:03,520 --> 00:44:05,059
Scott: But you should get on your hands and knees, that's good.

763
00:44:05,442 --> 00:44:05,716
Scott: Okay.

764
00:44:06,060 --> 00:44:06,220
Scott: Yeah.

765
00:44:06,942 --> 00:44:07,603
Scott: But, seriously...

766
00:44:16,360 --> 00:44:20,380
Rym: They're not, like, conceited, and they don't want you to be angry, they want to help you, usually.

767
00:44:21,260 --> 00:44:26,020
Rym: But don't take them for granted, because eventually they'll get sick of you and they won't help you anymore, otherwise.

768
00:44:26,580 --> 00:44:33,200
Scott: Yeah, you have to show the respect and put in the effort, and whatever they tell you, accept it as, like, the word of God.

769
00:44:33,660 --> 00:44:44,355
Rym: I made the mistake when I was in high school, very often, because people knew I was the computer guy, and they would... And I'd always make promises, like, someone would say, "Oh, I'm gonna build a new computer,".

770
00:44:44,375 --> 00:44:45,420
Rym: and I'd say, "Oh, tell you what.

771
00:44:46,901 --> 00:44:49,116
Rym: I'll tell you what parts to buy, you order them, and then I'll put it together for

772
00:44:49,157 --> 00:44:49,217
Rym: you.".

773
00:44:49,741 --> 00:44:53,560
Rym: And I'd say that all the time, because it was just, like, trivial to me, and I like messing around with computer-y bits.

774
00:44:54,400 --> 00:45:05,240
Rym: But then I actually had to do it, and I ended up being on the hook, because I'd build a computer for someone, and then a week later it would break, and they'd blame me, and I'd have to explain to them that, "No, it's because you're stupid.

775
00:45:05,320 --> 00:45:06,474
Rym: Don't ever talk to me again, I hate

776
00:45:06,494 --> 00:45:06,575
Rym: you.".

777
00:45:08,121 --> 00:45:11,502
Scott: And then they don't believe you, of course, because no one ever... That's the thing.

778
00:45:11,924 --> 00:45:13,590
Scott: In general, forget tech support.

779
00:45:13,850 --> 00:45:20,380
Scott: If someone doesn't blame themselves when something is their fault, and guess what, if there's a problem in your life, 90% of the time it's your fault.

780
00:45:21,280 --> 00:45:22,426
Rym: I don't know about 90%.

781
00:45:22,426 --> 00:45:25,280
Rym: I mean, it really depends on who you are and where you live.

782
00:45:25,782 --> 00:45:28,840
Rym: If you're living in Sudan or Darfur right now, it's probably not your fault.

783
00:45:28,960 --> 00:45:31,053
Scott: Well, no, because that's only one problem in your life.

784
00:45:31,113 --> 00:45:32,160
Scott: It's just a very big problem.

785
00:45:34,201 --> 00:45:36,632
Scott: The other 90% of the problems in your life are your fault.

786
00:45:36,652 --> 00:45:38,240
Scott: They're just all very small problems.

787
00:45:39,623 --> 00:45:42,160
Scott: That don't mean anything, because you have this one giant problem.

788
00:45:42,400 --> 00:45:45,520
Rym: I live in a horrible genocidal place, and oh, I didn't floss yesterday.

789
00:45:46,260 --> 00:45:46,824
Scott: Exactly.

790
00:45:47,490 --> 00:45:48,780
Scott: The not flossing is your fault.

791
00:45:49,920 --> 00:45:51,348
Rym: No, because floss wasn't available.

792
00:45:52,193 --> 00:45:53,260
Rym: Maybe you wanted to floss.

793
00:45:54,523 --> 00:45:55,338
Scott: You could have made do.

794
00:45:56,541 --> 00:45:58,460
Rym: With what, some cr- A string.

795
00:45:58,720 --> 00:45:59,699
Rym: You don't have a string.

796
00:46:00,260 --> 00:46:01,699
Scott: A shoelace, I don't frickin' know.

797
00:46:02,101 --> 00:46:03,238
Rym: They'd kill to have a shoelace.

798
00:46:03,520 --> 00:46:04,423
Scott: Yeah, probably.

799
00:46:05,086 --> 00:46:15,399
Scott: Anyway, the point is, is that when someone doesn't blame themselves for problems that are caused by their own doing or their lack of ability or

800
00:46:15,419 --> 00:46:20,220
Rym: whatever- Yeah, barring the fact that you might not realize it was your fault, as long as you accept it when someone shows that it was your fault.

801
00:46:20,840 --> 00:46:21,122
Scott: Mm-hmm.

802
00:46:21,142 --> 00:46:26,540
Scott: Don't go denying it was your fault and continuing to blame it on someone despite, I don't know, a mountain of evidence.

803
00:46:26,720 --> 00:46:28,512
Rym: Yeah, now this leads into number what, five?

804
00:46:28,734 --> 00:46:29,640
Rym: We're not really number 80s.

805
00:46:29,640 --> 00:46:30,156
Rym: Who cares?

806
00:46:30,763 --> 00:46:31,569
Rym: And this is the big one.

807
00:46:32,053 --> 00:46:33,060
Rym: Don't lie.

808
00:46:33,620 --> 00:46:41,797
Rym: If you say, "My RAM stopped working after I put it in a new computer," and I ask, "Did you put on wool socks and walk across the room with it in your

809
00:46:41,837 --> 00:46:42,159
Rym: hands?"

810
00:46:42,622 --> 00:46:44,499
Rym: and you did that, don't say no.

811
00:46:45,923 --> 00:46:47,238
Scott: Because you did, didn't you?

812
00:46:47,603 --> 00:46:47,880
Rym: Scott.

813
00:46:48,260 --> 00:46:48,643
Scott: Yeah, not me.

814
00:46:48,663 --> 00:46:49,367
Scott: The other Scott.

815
00:46:52,862 --> 00:47:01,500
Rym: Our friend Scott Jobs, we always rag on him for this because it was such a coincidence that one day he happened to just walk across a floor in wool socks with some RAM sticks in his hand.

816
00:47:01,780 --> 00:47:08,152
Scott: He was walking across a carpeted floor wearing wool socks and a sweater and his permanent sweater carrying RAM in his hand.

817
00:47:08,515 --> 00:47:09,180
Scott: What the hell?

818
00:47:09,440 --> 00:47:11,854
Scott: And everyone in the room was like, "Oh, my God!

819
00:47:11,914 --> 00:47:12,277
Rym: What are you

820
00:47:12,317 --> 00:47:12,679
Rym: doing?".

821
00:47:13,283 --> 00:47:15,079
Scott: Of course, that RAM is probably worth two cents now.

822
00:47:15,326 --> 00:47:15,560
Scott: Yeah.

823
00:47:15,721 --> 00:47:16,779
Scott: Even if it still worked.

824
00:47:16,980 --> 00:47:18,300
